§ 144. An interdict for obtaining possession is issued for the grantee of possession, beginning: ‘ What- ever portion of the goods 3 ’ and in- joining, that whatever portion of the goods, whereof possession has been granted to the claimant, is in the hands of one who holds as successor (civil, praetorian, or fide- commissary) or as mere possessor, such portion shall be delivered to the grantes of possession. He holds as successor who either is successor or thinks himself suc- cessor3 he holds as mere possessor who relies on no title but holds a portion or the ,whole of the in· heritance, knowing that he is not entitled. It is called an interdict for obtaining possession because it is only available for initiating pos- session, and is not granted to a person, who has already had and lost possession.
